  abstract = {THE HIERARCHICAL ORGANIZATION OF SMALL ARTIFICIAL GROUPS OF CAPTIVE MONKEYS IS THE EXPRESSION OF A CONTINUOUS LEARNING PROCESS. ONLY APPROACH/RETREAT INTERACTIONS CAN BE USED TO DETERMINE RANK. INTERACTIONS OF 11 ADULT AND SUBADULT PAPIO ANUBIS IN A BREEDING GROUP DURING 300 HR. WERE ANALYZED AND COMPARED WITH SIMILAR GROUPS OF P. HAMADRYAS AND M. MULATTA DESCRIBED BY OTHER WORKERS. BEHAVIOR OF THE SEXES IS QUANTITATIVELY, NOT QUALITATIVELY, DISTINGUISHED OUTSIDE MATING SITUATIONS; THE ARTIFICIAL GROUP STRUCTURE MAY GIVE SPURIOUS CORRELATIONS OF INTERSEXUAL BEHAVIOR WITH RANK. HIERARCHY IS NOT RIGID, AND PROBABLE METHOD OF CHANGING RANK CAN BE DEDUCED. HIERARCHY APPEARS TO BE MAINTAINED BY SUBORDINATES' BEHAVIOR PATTERNS AND BY LOW- RATHER THAN HIGH-RANKING ANIMALS. (18 REF.) (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2017 APA, all rights reserved)},
